data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False." MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Specialized assertions give clear failure messages
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Your original | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "expected 3, got N" on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(...)` | Says "value was null" on failure |

**Other collection assertions available:**

```csharp
Assert.Contains(expectedItem, collection);
Assert.DoesNotContain(unexpectedItem, collection);
Assert.IsEmpty(collection);
var single = Assert.ContainsSingle(collection); // exactly one element
```

Also consider sealing the test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance, per MSTest best practices.
